entry.title: Cassytha melantha
entry.content: Black sepals are a key feature of this species (hence the name melantha). Pic 3 has a small insect on it, possibly a Hemiptera.

entry.title: Correa backhouseana var. backhouseana
entry.content: This 100m of coastline contains possibly the only extant population of this species on mainland Australia.

entry.title: Notogrammitis billardierei
entry.content: Two plants photographed, one on a tree and one on a log.

entry.title: Comesperma ericinum
entry.content: Really unusual form in this swamp. Only two records locally, 20km either side of this one, and both from about 1890. ID by NW.

entry.title: Leptospermum continentale
entry.content: Verging on L. scoparium on some plants (eg. pic1) but leaves broadest at base and tapering to tip as per L. continentale (see especially pic2). Unusual forms of many species in this swamp.

entry.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa, Gleichenia dicarpa
Boronia parviflora
entry.content: Pale pink and white flowered plants. Large sepals are a key feature.

entry.title: Thelionema umbellatum
entry.content: Nearest records are at Anglesea and Portland. New record for Great Otway NP.

entry.title: Leucopogon parviflorus
entry.content: An unusual inland swamp form of L. parviflorus.

entry.title: Lepidosperma filiforme
entry.content: Leaf and stem similar and terete.

entry.title: Stylidium graminifolium s.s.
entry.content: Leaves were quite wide at maybe 3.1mm wide.

entry.title: Hakea ulicina
entry.content: Leaf width would suggest H. repullulans but the signs of vegetative new growth on the second pic means it can only be H. ulicina.
